node.text:
Dancing, music and embroidery have kept 18-year-old Rasani going through Nepal's latest COVID-19 lockdown.

As children and young people continue to struggle with the impacts of COVID-19, UNICEF and partners are working to make sure the adults they rely on have access to vaccines.

Only together can we beat this pandemic. That's why wealthy countries must donate doses now.

#OnlyTogether #DonateDosesNow

node.text:
13-year-old Emtinan is working towards becoming a pediatrician or a gynecologist. But violence has cost her a precious year of school in Yemen. 

The chaos of conflict and COVID-19 has wreaked havoc on children's access to education. Over 2 million children have been displaced by war, and just as many are out of school.

UNICEF is helping provide safe places to learn, materials and teacher training — but more than anything, the children of Yemen need peace.

node.title: The cost of war in Yemen

Dancing, music and embroidery have kept 18-year-old Rasani going through Nepal's latest COVID-19 lockdown.

As children and young people continue to struggle with the impacts of COVID-19, UNICEF and partners are working to make sure the adults they rely on have access to vaccines.

Only together can we beat this pandemic. That's why wealthy countries must donate doses now.

#OnlyTogether #DonateDosesNow

A  girl smiles at a menstrual health management session held at her UNICEF-supported school in Uganda.

When a crisis like the COVID-19 pandemic hits, we must make sure every girl’s right to manage her period safely and with dignity is upheld. © UNICEF/UN0419421/Adriko

node.text:
Peek-a-boo! Baby Mekdes has just been discharged from the hospital after recovering from measles in Ethiopia. But with a vaccine, she might not have needed treatment at all.
 
After decades of progress, global vaccination rates have plummeted due to disruptions caused by COVID-19. Over 17 million children didn’t receive a single vaccination last year. 

If we are to stop the heartbreak caused by preventable diseases, vaccines must be available to all.

#VaccinesWork

© UNICEF/UNI353201/Tesfaye

Through the pandemic, parents have masked up and braved COVID-19 disruptions to get their children vaccinated against deadly diseases like measles, tetanus and diphtheria. 
 
Despite the heroic efforts of health workers and parents, global vaccination rates plummeted last year, leaving 22.7 million children unprotected.
 
To prevent future outbreaks, investment in immunization programmes is needed now.
 
#VaccinesWork

node.text:
“I came because I want to protect my baby from bad diseases like measles,” said Annet, after walking to reach a health centre in Uganda during the COVID-19 outbreak. “I didn’t mind the distance because all I wanted was to have my baby immunized. I am even willing to support mothers who can’t walk this far. I volunteered to support my neighbour, who has twins, by helping her carry one baby.”

Despite the pandemic, parents are determined to continue their children’s vaccinations, and we’re urging all governments to make that possible. 

#vaccineswork
